**Caterpillar (NYSE: CAT): Why Analysts Are Forecasting 15% Annual EBITDA G=
rowth Through 2030**

Caterpillar is the world's largest maker of heavy construction and mining e=
quipment (think the yellow bulldozers, excavators, and dump trucks at every=
 major job site), but the most important part of the business today isn't c=
onstruction at all. It's the Power & Energy segment, which builds the large=
 diesel engines, gas turbines, and generators that supply on-site electrici=
ty to data centers, oil and gas operations, and industrial plants. That seg=
ment is now the company's fastest-growing business and the entire reason an=
alysts model EBITDA to roughly double from about $14 billion in 2025 to nea=
rly $30 billion by 2030.

The growth thesis sits on a few clear pillars. First, AI-driven data center=
 demand is reshaping the order book. Power & Energy revenue grew 44% year-o=
ver-year in Q4 2025, and management has now committed to nearly tripling la=
rge reciprocating engine capacity by 2030 (up from a 2x target set just a y=
ear ago). Second, backlog visibility is unusually strong. Total enterprise =
backlog hit a record $63 billion in Q1 2026, up 79% from a year earlier, gi=
ving multi-year revenue cover that traditional cyclical equipment makers ra=
rely have.

https://app.tikr.com/stock/about?cid=3D259378&tid=3D2598619=20

Third, the mix shift toward prime power generators (which run continuously =
and pull in ongoing service revenue) drives high-margin recurring sales. Th=
at's why EBITDA margins are forecast to expand from roughly 21% in 2025 to =
nearly 30% by 2030. Caterpillar also raised its long-term revenue growth ta=
rget to 6-9% annually through 2030, up from 5-7%. Tariff headwinds of aroun=
d $2.6 billion in 2026 are the biggest near-term risk, but the structural s=
etup of hyperscaler power demand plus services growth plus capacity investm=
ent is what gives the forecast credibility.

